71
00:03:29,280 --> 00:03:40,460
Let's talk about the invariance of the laws of nature

72
00:03:40,460 --> 00:03:43,340
under various kinds of operations.

73
00:03:43,340 --> 00:03:45,660
Of course, what I really have in mind is, of course,

74
00:03:45,660 --> 00:03:47,840
Lorentz transformations.

75
00:03:47,840 --> 00:03:51,000
The fact that the laws of nature do not change when we make

76
00:03:51,000 --> 00:03:53,780
a Lorentz transformation.

77
00:03:53,780 --> 00:03:57,280
But let's talk about the strategy for cooking up laws.

78
00:03:57,280 --> 00:03:57,780
OK.

79
00:03:58,280 --> 00:04:04,220
Which look the same in every reference frame.

80
00:04:04,220 --> 00:04:11,360
The strategy is to express those laws in a form which really

81
00:04:11,360 --> 00:04:18,620
doesn't depend on any particular choice of coordinates.

82
00:04:18,620 --> 00:04:22,440
To express the laws in some physical way that, as I said,

83
00:04:22,440 --> 00:04:25,580
that doesn't depend on specific coordinates.

84
00:04:25,580 --> 00:04:27,900
And then choose a set of coordinates,

85
00:04:28,280 --> 00:04:33,420
and rewrite what you've expressed in a language appropriate to those coordinates.

86
00:04:33,420 --> 00:04:33,920
An example.

87
00:04:33,920 --> 00:04:42,820
The shortest distance between two points, the definition of a straight line,

88
00:04:42,820 --> 00:04:48,780
is the shortest distance between two points, the shortest trajectory between two points.

89
00:04:48,780 --> 00:04:57,740
You can figure out what a straight line is, connecting a pair of points, by sticking a

90
00:04:57,740 --> 00:04:59,520
thumbtack.

91
00:04:59,520 --> 00:05:06,780
Please don't stick thumbtacks in the blackboards and the whiteboards, but you could.

92
00:05:06,780 --> 00:05:14,160
Stick a couple of thumbtacks in, take a string, pull it as tight as you can,

93
00:05:14,160 --> 00:05:19,300
and that will guarantee that you've found the shortest distance between those two points,

94
00:05:19,300 --> 00:05:21,340
and that you will call a straight line.

95
00:05:21,340 --> 00:05:25,040
In other words, the law for a straight line, this is not actually a law of physics now,

96
00:05:25,040 --> 00:05:27,700
this is the definition of a straight line, but it's

97
00:05:27,740 --> 00:05:34,980
been defined in a way that made no reference to any particular coordinates.

98
00:05:34,980 --> 00:05:40,460
An example of a law of physics that's closely related to this is that the path of a light

99
00:05:40,460 --> 00:05:44,320
ray between two points is a straight line.

100
00:05:44,320 --> 00:05:46,020
That's a law.

101
00:05:46,020 --> 00:05:51,420
And now it can be stated that the path of a light ray between two points is the shortest

102
00:05:51,420 --> 00:05:54,200
distance between those two points.

103
00:05:54,200 --> 00:05:56,420
That's a light ray in a vacuum.

104
00:05:56,420 --> 00:05:57,520
Generally.

105
00:05:57,520 --> 00:06:02,840
The generalization of that for light moving through various kinds of materials is that

106
00:06:02,840 --> 00:06:08,340
the time that it takes a light ray to go from one point to another is the shortest possible

107
00:06:08,340 --> 00:06:10,340
time.

108
00:06:10,340 --> 00:06:18,440
Alright, so those, and notice again, I did not use any definition of spatial coordinates

109
00:06:18,440 --> 00:06:20,700
in expressing those laws.

110
00:06:20,700 --> 00:06:26,280
Those laws were expressed in a coordinate independent way.

111
00:06:26,280 --> 00:06:27,360
But then, I

112
00:06:27,360 --> 00:06:33,560
can then use coordinates to build myself up with mathematics and to solve some equations

113
00:06:33,560 --> 00:06:34,920
involving those laws.

114
00:06:34,920 --> 00:06:36,600
Let me give you an example.

115
00:06:36,600 --> 00:06:42,740
Just exactly this law here, that light travels along the shortest path, or just the problem

116
00:06:42,740 --> 00:06:45,240
of finding the shortest path between two points.

117
00:06:45,240 --> 00:06:50,840
Alright, once I know that the shortest path, that's what I'm looking for, is the shortest

118
00:06:50,840 --> 00:06:54,120
path, I take some coordinates, x and y, I include them in the randomization.

119
00:06:54,120 --> 00:06:55,360
So, I take the coordinates, x and y, and put that in a coordinate.

120
00:06:55,360 --> 00:06:56,360
So here, close the cap.

121
00:06:56,360 --> 00:06:57,360
So, all right, so now, that's the story for light.

122
00:06:57,360 --> 00:07:01,240
I label the two points of interest

123
00:07:01,240 --> 00:07:03,340
I give them coordinates

124
00:07:03,340 --> 00:07:05,480
x1, y1, x2, y2

125
00:07:05,480 --> 00:07:06,820
I won't bother right now

126
00:07:06,820 --> 00:07:10,580
and then I write down

127
00:07:10,580 --> 00:07:12,420
well, first of all

128
00:07:12,420 --> 00:07:15,060
I imagine a curve connecting them

129
00:07:15,060 --> 00:07:17,600
I imagine a curve

130
00:07:17,600 --> 00:07:18,760
in fact, I'm going to imagine

131
00:07:18,760 --> 00:07:20,820
all possible curves connecting them

132
00:07:20,820 --> 00:07:23,020
and I break up that curve

133
00:07:23,020 --> 00:07:24,100
into little segments

134
00:07:24,100 --> 00:07:26,520
each little segment

135
00:07:26,520 --> 00:07:29,440
can be characterized by a differential

136
00:07:29,440 --> 00:07:31,740
meaning a small displacement

137
00:07:31,740 --> 00:07:33,360
dx and dy

138
00:07:33,360 --> 00:07:36,240
so let's take a little displacement

139
00:07:36,240 --> 00:07:36,980
over here

140
00:07:36,980 --> 00:07:38,900
and label it dx

141
00:07:38,900 --> 00:07:40,540
and dy

142
00:07:40,540 --> 00:07:43,440
eventually, of course

143
00:07:43,440 --> 00:07:44,720
we're going to go to the limit

144
00:07:44,720 --> 00:07:47,000
where we chop it up into smaller and smaller pieces

145
00:07:47,000 --> 00:07:47,980
and do some calculus

146
00:07:47,980 --> 00:07:50,860
but for the moment, just call them dx and dy

147
00:07:50,860 --> 00:07:55,080
and now let's write the length of the curve

148
00:07:55,080 --> 00:07:56,500
the length of the curve

149
00:07:56,500 --> 00:07:57,600
is just the summation

150
00:07:57,600 --> 00:08:00,960
over all of these little differential elements

151
00:08:00,960 --> 00:08:03,220
of the length of each differential element

152
00:08:03,220 --> 00:08:05,620
the length of each differential element

153
00:08:05,620 --> 00:08:07,380
we can write ds

154
00:08:07,380 --> 00:08:09,740
s for length

155
00:08:09,740 --> 00:08:11,580
I'm not sure why I use s for length

156
00:08:11,580 --> 00:08:13,280
except it's traditional to do so

157
00:08:13,280 --> 00:08:14,820
and that's equal

158
00:08:14,820 --> 00:08:17,380
to the square root of dx squared

159
00:08:17,380 --> 00:08:18,500
plus dy squared

160
00:08:18,500 --> 00:08:21,680
that's of course the Pythagorean theorem

161
00:08:21,680 --> 00:08:24,540
it does not depend

162
00:08:24,540 --> 00:08:26,480
on what the orientation of the curve is

163
00:08:26,480 --> 00:08:29,380
but on what the orientation of the axes are

164
00:08:29,380 --> 00:08:32,240
with any orientation for the axes

165
00:08:32,240 --> 00:08:34,480
as long, incidentally

166
00:08:34,480 --> 00:08:37,480
as long as I use the same units

167
00:08:37,480 --> 00:08:39,240
for x and y

168
00:08:39,240 --> 00:08:41,240
I would get a rather bizarre expression

169
00:08:41,240 --> 00:08:42,980
as I've emphasized several times

170
00:08:42,980 --> 00:08:44,980
if I used meters for x

171
00:08:44,980 --> 00:08:47,480
and feet for y

172
00:08:47,480 --> 00:08:50,240
but as long as I use the same units

173
00:08:50,240 --> 00:08:54,580
it doesn't matter which way I orient the axes

174
00:08:54,580 --> 00:08:55,580
on the blackboard

175
00:08:55,580 --> 00:08:57,580
I'm just going to use the same

176
00:08:57,580 --> 00:08:59,580
and the length of a little differential element

177
00:08:59,580 --> 00:09:00,580
is still the same

178
00:09:00,580 --> 00:09:02,580
and now I add them all up

179
00:09:02,580 --> 00:09:04,580
I add them up by integrating

180
00:09:04,580 --> 00:09:06,580
s for the total length

181
00:09:06,580 --> 00:09:08,580
becomes the integral

182
00:09:08,580 --> 00:09:11,580
which is just the sum of all these little differential elements here

183
00:09:11,580 --> 00:09:15,580
square root of dx squared plus dy squared

184
00:09:15,580 --> 00:09:17,580
now that's a strange look

185
00:09:17,580 --> 00:09:20,580
for some of you that may be a bit of a strange looking expression

186
00:09:20,580 --> 00:09:23,580
a square root of dx squared plus dy squared

187
00:09:23,580 --> 00:09:24,580
it's not really that strange

188
00:09:24,580 --> 00:09:25,580
you're going to have to do a little bit of a test

189
00:09:25,580 --> 00:09:26,580
you could think of y

190
00:09:26,580 --> 00:09:30,580
you could think of x as the independent variable

191
00:09:30,580 --> 00:09:34,580
and then rewrite this in another form

192
00:09:34,580 --> 00:09:36,580
integral

193
00:09:36,580 --> 00:09:40,580
let's take out a factor of dx

194
00:09:40,580 --> 00:09:41,580
and now in the square root

195
00:09:41,580 --> 00:09:44,580
since I've taken out a factor of dx

196
00:09:44,580 --> 00:09:47,580
that means I should divide what's in the square root

197
00:09:47,580 --> 00:09:49,580
by dx squared

198
00:09:49,580 --> 00:09:54,580
and that just becomes one plus dy by dx squared

199
00:09:55,580 --> 00:09:57,580
dy by dx squared

200
00:09:57,580 --> 00:10:01,580
that's just a derivative of the dependent variable y

201
00:10:01,580 --> 00:10:03,580
with respect to x

202
00:10:03,580 --> 00:10:05,580
and this is a perfectly good integral

203
00:10:05,580 --> 00:10:08,580
if you know what y of x is

204
00:10:08,580 --> 00:10:11,580
that's the length between the two points

205
00:10:11,580 --> 00:10:14,580
and now you can set yourself the task

206
00:10:14,580 --> 00:10:16,580
let me find the curve

207
00:10:16,580 --> 00:10:19,580
which gives the smallest value for this

208
00:10:19,580 --> 00:10:22,580
that connects two points

209
00:10:22,580 --> 00:10:24,580
this of course is very similar

210
00:10:24,580 --> 00:10:26,580
to the principle of least action

211
00:10:26,580 --> 00:10:31,580
which says that the trajectory of a particle in space-time

212
00:10:31,580 --> 00:10:35,580
sweeps out a path of least action

213
00:10:35,580 --> 00:10:38,580
again, action being some kind of integral

214
00:10:38,580 --> 00:10:41,580
of a Lagrangian

215
00:10:41,580 --> 00:10:42,580
very similar kind of thing

216
00:10:42,580 --> 00:10:44,580
but the main point here

217
00:10:44,580 --> 00:10:48,580
is that we've expressed the original law

218
00:10:48,580 --> 00:10:50,580
without coordinates

219
00:10:50,580 --> 00:10:52,580
and therefore we can be sure

220
00:10:52,580 --> 00:10:53,580
that when we introduce coordinates

221
00:10:53,580 --> 00:10:57,580
the answer will not depend on our choice of coordinates

222
00:10:57,580 --> 00:10:58,580
yes sir

223
00:10:58,580 --> 00:11:01,580
can you define distance without coordinates?

224
00:11:01,580 --> 00:11:04,580
uh...

225
00:11:04,580 --> 00:11:06,580
sure

226
00:11:06,580 --> 00:11:08,580
tape measure

227
00:11:08,580 --> 00:11:11,580
of course the tape measure has coordinates along it

228
00:11:11,580 --> 00:11:13,580
but the point is

229
00:11:13,580 --> 00:11:17,580
it doesn't matter how you reorient the axes

230
00:11:17,580 --> 00:11:20,580
the tape measure will always give the same expression

231
00:11:20,580 --> 00:11:23,580
so it was defined by

232
00:11:23,580 --> 00:11:26,580
the string or the tape measure connecting the two points

233
00:11:26,580 --> 00:11:29,580
but without regard to how I chose the x-y axes

234
00:11:29,580 --> 00:11:30,580
but then

235
00:11:30,580 --> 00:11:33,580
in an attempt to actually mathematically implement

236
00:11:33,580 --> 00:11:35,580
the mathematical problem

237
00:11:35,580 --> 00:11:37,580
I introduced a set of coordinates

238
00:11:37,580 --> 00:11:40,580
to express the problem in a mathematical form

239
00:11:40,580 --> 00:11:43,580
and so yes, I think the problem is expressed

240
00:11:43,580 --> 00:11:46,580
without coordinates

241
00:11:46,580 --> 00:11:48,580
it's a good question

242
00:11:48,580 --> 00:11:52,580
but for the moment I'll leave it hang as

243
00:11:52,580 --> 00:11:56,580
in the way that I said it

244
00:11:56,580 --> 00:11:59,580
okay, now, so that's an example

245
00:11:59,580 --> 00:12:02,580
now what went into that example

246
00:12:02,580 --> 00:12:04,580
the most important thing that went into that example

247
00:12:04,580 --> 00:12:07,580
mathematically was Pythagoras' theorem

248
00:12:07,580 --> 00:12:10,580
that the distance between two points

249
00:12:10,580 --> 00:12:13,580
is the square root of the sum of the squares

250
00:12:13,580 --> 00:12:14,580
and that does not

251
00:12:14,580 --> 00:12:16,580
the sum of the squares of the coordinates

252
00:12:16,580 --> 00:12:18,580
and it has exactly the same form

253
00:12:18,580 --> 00:12:20,580
if you were to tilt the axes

254
00:12:20,580 --> 00:12:22,580
that in itself

255
00:12:22,580 --> 00:12:25,580
is an expression of invariance

256
00:12:25,580 --> 00:12:28,580
that the distance between two neighboring points

257
00:12:28,580 --> 00:12:30,580
is invariant, meaning to say

258
00:12:30,580 --> 00:12:34,580
it doesn't depend on your coordinates

259
00:12:34,580 --> 00:12:36,580
and of course we're familiar with this

260
00:12:36,580 --> 00:12:39,580
we've gone through it several times

261
00:12:39,580 --> 00:12:43,580
dx squared plus dy squared

262
00:12:43,580 --> 00:12:45,580
doesn't depend on your choice of coordinates

263
00:12:45,580 --> 00:12:47,580
and the way to check that

264
00:12:47,580 --> 00:12:50,580
which is exactly the sorts of things we've checked up till now

265
00:12:50,580 --> 00:12:52,580
is we've taken a coordinate set

266
00:12:52,580 --> 00:12:55,580
and we've rotated the coordinate system

267
00:12:55,580 --> 00:12:57,580
rotated the coordinate system

268
00:12:57,580 --> 00:13:02,580
x, y, x prime, y prime, theta

269
00:13:02,580 --> 00:13:04,580
an angle between them

270
00:13:04,580 --> 00:13:08,580
and we've discovered that the law of transformation

271
00:13:08,580 --> 00:13:12,580
the mathematical law of rotation of coordinates

272
00:13:12,580 --> 00:13:16,580
is the law which keeps

273
00:13:16,580 --> 00:13:19,580
x squared plus y squared fixed

274
00:13:19,580 --> 00:13:21,580
dx squared plus dy squared fixed

